<div id="review_633381565" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/633381565" />
    <a title="Frankie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/853659-frankie"><img alt="Frankie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1322158484p2/853659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/633381565?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frankie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frankie" href="/user/show/853659-frankie">Frankie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/853659-frankie?shelf=british">british</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer633381565" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14464542926505579523">Buchan&apos;s Hannay is a clear precursor to Fleming&apos;s Bond, with the one major exception forced by a more innocent time and readership - Hannay is no womanizer. As an espionage novel it&apos;s quite good and an enjoyable read. It&apos;s written broadly for all ages, certainly simple enough to be understood by an entire generation of British boys who would probably later serve in WWII. Buchan wrote five Hannay books (the first is <i>The Thirty-Nine Steps</i> and this is the second) as what he called &apos;his contribution</span>
  <span id="freeText14464542926505579523" style="display:none">Buchan's Hannay is a clear precursor to Fleming's Bond, with the one major exception forced by a more innocent time and readership - Hannay is no womanizer. As an espionage novel it's quite good and an enjoyable read. It's written broadly for all ages, certainly simple enough to be understood by an entire generation of British boys who would probably later serve in WWII. Buchan wrote five Hannay books (the first is <i>The Thirty-Nine Steps</i> and this is the second) as what he called 'his contribution to the war effort'. It goes without saying that some historical accuracy as well as violence is muted.<br /><br />Buchan writes adventure, so you must try to forgive him the numerous plot coincidences, nationalistic stereotypes and chauvinism. WWI Europe was, especially for Britain, a time of fair play - in a manner of speaking. Germans were considered bad guys but only in a sporting, war-game sort of way. At least, that's the impression I get from WWI era literature and film, and as well in comparison to the accelerated brutality of WWII. Perhaps the second war would've been less harrowing if the Germans had not been laughed at so heartily.<br /><br />The Muslim world of the book is treated lightly, though words like <i>fatwa</i> and <i>jihad</i> are bound to prick up any contemporary reader's ear. I hoped to gain some knowledge of the early 20th century Arab world, but there is little in the way of exposition aside from standard spy lingo. I suppose it's better to be uninformed than ill informed.<br /><br />I found it curious that the character Hilda is so vilified throughout the novel, yet fails to live up to her supposed villainy. Hannay and his spy buddies, established heroes on the European front, consider Germans to be of little challenge, so it's significant that their residence in Constantinople and Anatolia is fraught with unprepared-for dangers. Buchan's version of Islamists have dark sorcery on their side, so it seems incongruous to set a German woman as their leader. Not all of his characters are so staged. Hilda seems to be an example of Buchan playing it safe, in a near propagandized move to relabel all worldly threat under the German heading. There are, however, greatly sympathetic German and Turkish characters. <br /><br />This is my first foray into the spy genre. I'd recommend this book, since it's certainly entertaining and a quick read with little to analyze philosophically. I gave it only three stars instead of four, because of its unabashed jingoism.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14464542926505579523" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

