<div id="review_1080311877" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1080311877" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26847889-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464921161p2/26847889.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1080311877?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/26847889-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18816990-greenmantle">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1080311877" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11060328134783369031">I believe &quot;Greenmantle&quot; falls squarely into that elusive genre, the &quot;ripping good yarn.&quot; This tale of a top secret spy mission during World War I is all adventure and utter fun. &quot;Greenmantle&quot; is actually the second in a series of such yarns following the adventures of British officer and colonial engineer Richard Hannay. Though, it isn&apos;t necessary to have read &quot;The Thirty-nine Steps&quot; to jump into the second installment, you may want to brush up on your World War I history a little bit so you und</span>
  <span id="freeText11060328134783369031" style="display:none">I believe "Greenmantle" falls squarely into that elusive genre, the "ripping good yarn." This tale of a top secret spy mission during World War I is all adventure and utter fun. "Greenmantle" is actually the second in a series of such yarns following the adventures of British officer and colonial engineer Richard Hannay. Though, it isn't necessary to have read "The Thirty-nine Steps" to jump into the second installment, you may want to brush up on your World War I history a little bit so you understand the shifting alliances, allegiances, and enmities between and among the Ottoman Turks, the Young Turks, imperial Germany, and the Kurds. I actually only discovered John Buchan's novels because they were mentioned in "A Peace to End all Peace: The Fall of the Ottoman Empire and the Creation of the Modern Middle East." So, I had the historical context fresh in my mind. <br /><br />Keep in mind, however, that this novel is one of the first popular spy thrillers ever written. So, there are a few plot devices we might see as a little corny or cliché because authors since Buchan's time have used them so freely. Also, our hero Richard Hannay is the James Bond of his day. And like James Bond, he's a little too clever, lucky, bulletproof, multi-lingual, and gravity defying than real humans. Apparently, it's all standard issue for servants of His/Her Magesty's Secret Service. <br /><br />One further side note: Because of the time when "Greenmantle" was written, it contains some references and idioms which, rightfully so, we consider quite racist today. I also noted a single obliquely homophobic remark.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11060328134783369031" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

