<div id="review_2544554710" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2544554710" />
    <a title="Phil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5915778-phil"><img alt="Phil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1371309664p2/5915778.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2544554710?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phil" href="/user/show/5915778-phil">Phil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5915778-phil?shelf=guardian-1000-books-list">guardian-1000-books-list</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5915778-phil?shelf=ebook">ebook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2544554710" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer618621083510387987">The older I get, the less leeway I give racism, sexism and homophobia when it’s not a character’s attribute but the author’s views seeping through. This novel is full of it. The jingoism I let off because it’s propaganda for WW1, but all the references to “being a white man”, Hanny boasting of his time as a “nigger driver”, the Jews controlling the world and Stumm’s penchant for soft fabrics and luxury that turns Hannay’s stomach could have all been dropped and not affected the story one bit.<br/><br/>The</span>
  <span id="freeText618621083510387987" style="display:none">The older I get, the less leeway I give racism, sexism and homophobia when it’s not a character’s attribute but the author’s views seeping through. This novel is full of it. The jingoism I let off because it’s propaganda for WW1, but all the references to “being a white man”, Hanny boasting of his time as a “nigger driver”, the Jews controlling the world and Stumm’s penchant for soft fabrics and luxury that turns Hannay’s stomach could have all been dropped and not affected the story one bit.<br /><br />Then there’s the story, which doesn’t have The Thirty Nine Steps’s advantage of extreme brevity. Some might allow a continual stream of preposterous coincidences by because they’re dragged along by the suspenseful plot line, but every time Hannay met up with a chum at a random spot on a random day at a random time when the entire continent is available, I was pulled right out of the story to go and roll my eye.<br /><br />And the denouement relies not only on a dream literally coming true, but a secondary character meeting ANOTHER foreign chum on a separate continent who he just happened to be best mates with two decades earlier.<br /><br />Add into this the idea of public school boys being inherently superheroes who can not only break their arm and still ride a horse into battle but also be a blond haired British lord and convince a country that he’s an Arabic prophet. This boys own “isn’t it jolly being in the trenches” tone also got on my wick.<br /><br />Sorry, but not for me. I’ve given it 3 stars because it wasn’t dreadful.</span>
  <a data-text-id="618621083510387987" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


